 details and command over colloquial language. While calling up a range of voices, her works are marked by a distinct voice, simultaneously slightly naïve and deeply ironic. She is a keen observer of the female condition, recounting gendered tribulations with awareness and amusement. From spiritual rabbits and biblical zoos to poems about loss and comics about poetry, Goralik's colorful language and pervasive dark comedy capture the heights of ridiculousness and the depths of grief.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAuthors, Russiany21st century. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh1 aMorse, Ainsley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVassileva, Maria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVinokour, Maya, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2017z978311065472108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311054330840uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/gora1835040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231544979423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231544979.jpg  a978-3-11-054330-8  CUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017b2017  a978-3-11-065472-1  CUP eBook Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK